<title>Gotham Is Pro Wrestling With Batman Characters</title>
<link>https://www.geek.com/television/gotham-is-pro-wrestling-with-batman-characters-1722305/?source</link>
<guid isPermaLink="true" >https://www.geek.com/television/gotham-is-pro-wrestling-with-batman-characters-1722305/?source</guid>
<description>&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Gotham &lt;/em&gt;on some level has always been wrestling. It’s had surprising villain turns, sudden betrayals and most of the action consists of over-the-top costumed characters punching each other. The overarching story is melodramatic and ridiculous, but played completely straight. This show is basically the result of a kid who’s really into wrestling a bunch of action figures. Last night’s episode leaned all the way into that idea, with much of the action taking place inside an actual ring. It led to a stand-out episode in what was already a particularly strong season.&lt;/p&gt;&amp;#13;
&lt;p&gt;It really does feel like &lt;em&gt;Gotham &lt;/em&gt;has finally hit its stride after three years. As much as I liked seasons two and three, they both fell into familiar patterns of boring, overstuffed episodes setting up the fun ridiculous setpieces. But with each season, the show has gotten better at telling its story. It’s embraced the ridiculousness and allowed itself to build up to those moments. That also gives it the room to focus on deeper character-driven stories alongside all that insane action. When an episode can deliver both ridiculous wrestling-style action and touching character drama, that’s when &lt;em&gt;Gotham &lt;/em&gt;really shines.&lt;/p&gt;&amp;#13;
&amp;#13;
&lt;p&gt;Much of this episode took place in the underground fight club in The Narrows. Ed Nygma has moved beyond just being Solomon Grundy’s manager, and now he’s part of the show himself. He does a fantastic impression of Penguin, getting the crowd all riled up to take down an authority figure before Grundy comes out and pretends to beat him up. It’s honestly a decent bit of sketch comedy. I’d go to something like this in New York, if it wasn’t for all the murder. The Riddler’s impression of Penguin really is the best part of the show. He has every little mannerism and movement down perfectly. Nygma may have claimed to hate Penguin, but clearly a lot of love went into that impression. Penguin isn’t too happy about it though. Once word of the impression reaches him, he sends Barbara, Tabitha and Selina to collect Ed and bring him back. Once they do their debt for stealing from licensed criminals will be paid.&lt;/p&gt;&amp;#13;
&lt;div id=&quot;attachment_1722328&quot; class=&quot;wp-caption alignnone&quot; readability=&quot;33&quot;&gt;&lt;img class=&quot;size-full wp-image-1722328&quot; src=&quot;https://www.geek.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/11/Gotham-408_SCN6_8_DG0703_hires1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;690&quot; height=&quot;388&quot; srcset=&quot;https://www.geek.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/11/Gotham-408_SCN6_8_DG0703_hires1.jpg 690w, https://www.geek.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/11/Gotham-408_SCN6_8_DG0703_hires1-300x169.jpg 300w, https://www.geek.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/11/Gotham-408_SCN6_8_DG0703_hires1-625x352.jpg 625w, https://www.geek.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/11/Gotham-408_SCN6_8_DG0703_hires1-650x366.jpg 650w, https://www.geek.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/11/Gotham-408_SCN6_8_DG0703_hires1-141x80.jpg 141w, https://www.geek.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/11/Gotham-408_SCN6_8_DG0703_hires1-130x73.jpg 130w&quot; sizes=&quot;(max-width: 690px) 100vw, 690px&quot;/&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;wp-caption-text&quot;&gt;Camren Bicondova, Erin Richards and Jessica Lucas (Cr: David Giesbrecht/FOX)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;&amp;#13;
&lt;p&gt;As soon as they arrive, the point of this story becomes clear. It gets Barbara in the same room with Lee and Tabitha in the same room with Grundy. The characters immediately split off to fulfill the dramatic potential of the situation, leaving Selina as the only one focused on the job. The Barbara and Lee conversation doesn’t move the story forward at all, but it sure is fun to watch these two women bicker and insult each other. Lee is all the way done with Barbara’s crap and it’s amazing to see. Tabitha’s scenes are a little sadder, as Butch/Grundy clearly doesn’t recognize her. He doesn’t even believe her when she tells him that Ed Nygma wasn’t his friend. Worse still, when they get caught dragging Nygma out, Selina calls “code of the Narrows,” meaning they’ll settle it in the ring. Their best fighter (Tabitha) against Grundy. Winner gets Ed. So Tabitha is forced to fight her former lover, whom she just found out is still alive. That’s messed up.&lt;/p&gt;&amp;#13;
&lt;p&gt;Even sadder is the fact that with Grundy has started flashing back to his former life every time he takes a significantly large blow to the head. The moment where he recognizes Tabitha just before she knocks him out with that hammer-bat thing is surprisingly affecting. The moment had a ton of methodical build up and it paid off. I’m not even disappointed that this is as much as we see of their story this week. If &lt;em&gt;Gotham &lt;/em&gt;can keep telling these character-driven stories at this subtle, effective pace, I’m OK waiting until next week to see what happens next. Of course, Firefly shows up and puts a stop to the action in the ring. The Sirens had a deadline, and they missed it. Now, Firefly is threatening to burn down the fight club and bring Nygma in herself. This is the point where the episode really feels like wrestling. They packed so many loyalty-turns and surprise betrayals into such a short amount of time, it would have been wrong if this scene took place anywhere other than inside a ring. The long and short of it is the leader of the fight club turned out to be working for Penguin, Lee exposed her and Barbara shot her. Barbara declared that she, Tabitha and Selina are no longer working for Penguin, and the denizens of the Narrows accepted Lee as the new leader. She celebrated by buying everyone a round. As ridiculous as all that sounds to type out, it all felt so natural thanks to some truly brilliant pacing this season.&lt;/p&gt;&amp;#13;
&amp;#13;
&lt;div id=&quot;attachment_1722329&quot; class=&quot;wp-caption alignnone&quot; readability=&quot;32&quot;&gt;&lt;img class=&quot;size-full wp-image-1722329&quot; src=&quot;https://www.geek.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/11/Gotham-408_SCN21_DG1601_hires1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;690&quot; height=&quot;388&quot; srcset=&quot;https://www.geek.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/11/Gotham-408_SCN21_DG1601_hires1.jpg 690w, https://www.geek.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/11/Gotham-408_SCN21_DG1601_hires1-300x169.jpg 300w, https://www.geek.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/11/Gotham-408_SCN21_DG1601_hires1-625x352.jpg 625w, https://www.geek.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/11/Gotham-408_SCN21_DG1601_hires1-650x366.jpg 650w, https://www.geek.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/11/Gotham-408_SCN21_DG1601_hires1-141x80.jpg 141w, https://www.geek.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/11/Gotham-408_SCN21_DG1601_hires1-130x73.jpg 130w&quot; sizes=&quot;(max-width: 690px) 100vw, 690px&quot;/&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;wp-caption-text&quot;&gt;Jessica Lucas (Cr: David Giesbrecht/FOX)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;&amp;#13;
&lt;p&gt;Penguin didn’t have nearly as much to do, but his story was interesting nonetheless. At Sofia’s suggestion that he find an interest outside of work, he takes to training a young boy he sees getting picked on. He teaches the boy the ways of deception and manipulation. This is an aspect of Penguin’s character that was introduced last season, but was dropped just as quickly. It’s nice to see them return to it. He really feels for kids that are bullied because he sees himself in them. Of course, his lessons and methods of comfort are a little… sadistic, but that’s just who he is. Watching him mold Gotham’s next great supervillain is almost touching. It also gives him a chance to reflect on lessons he’s already learned and applied them to his current situation. That means he finally figures out Sofia may not be entirely on the up and up. She probably has another plan up her sleeve to win back Penguin’s trust, but her tactics probably aren’t going to work much longer. &lt;em&gt;Gotham &lt;/em&gt;is setting up a war between Sofia Falcone and Oswald Cobblepot, and I’m really excited to see it.&lt;/p&gt;&amp;#13;
&lt;p&gt;Finally, there was the story of Jim Gordon and Harvey Bullock. &lt;em&gt;Gotham &lt;/em&gt;took some time off from the Professor Pyg story, but the repercussions of last week’s trap weigh heavily over the GCPD. The commissioner wants Gordon to replace Bullock as captain and Gordon desperately doesn’t want to betray his friend. Even though it’s led to a significant shortage of sarcastic Bullock quotes, the growing wedge between Gordon and Bullock has been one of the best told stories this season. Gordon really doesn’t want to take the job from Harvey. He wants to give Harvey one more chance. That chance is presenting all the cops who were shot in The Narrows incident with the bullets they were shot with. It’s an informal ceremony, but an important one for the morale of the department. He can’t even do that. He asks Gordon to meet him there and doesn’t show up, forcing Gordon to present the bullets. In that moment, Bullock proves to Gordon that he can’t do the job, so Gordon is forced to take it from him. Even he knows it’s not a clean decision. He knows that Sofia Falcone pushed the commissioner to hire Gordon. As much as he tries to refuse her help, she has some amount of control over him. It’s the saddest, most serious story &lt;em&gt;Gotham &lt;/em&gt;had this week and it’s only going to get sadder.&lt;/p&gt;&amp;#13;
&lt;div id=&quot;attachment_1722330&quot; class=&quot;wp-caption alignnone&quot; readability=&quot;32&quot;&gt;&lt;img class=&quot;size-full wp-image-1722330&quot; src=&quot;https://www.geek.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/11/Gotham-408_SCN21_DG1823_hires1.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;690&quot; height=&quot;388&quot; srcset=&quot;https://www.geek.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/11/Gotham-408_SCN21_DG1823_hires1.jpg 690w, https://www.geek.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/11/Gotham-408_SCN21_DG1823_hires1-300x169.jpg 300w, https://www.geek.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/11/Gotham-408_SCN21_DG1823_hires1-625x352.jpg 625w, https://www.geek.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/11/Gotham-408_SCN21_DG1823_hires1-650x366.jpg 650w, https://www.geek.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/11/Gotham-408_SCN21_DG1823_hires1-141x80.jpg 141w, https://www.geek.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/11/Gotham-408_SCN21_DG1823_hires1-130x73.jpg 130w&quot; sizes=&quot;(max-width: 690px) 100vw, 690px&quot;/&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;wp-caption-text&quot;&gt;Morena Baccarin and guest star Marina Benedict (Cr: David Giesbrecht/FOX)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;&amp;#13;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Gotham &lt;/em&gt;has really upped its storytelling game this season, and no episode is a better showcase of that improvement than this one. Even with all the over-the-top ridiculous things that happened, the progression felt natural and earned. &lt;em&gt;Gotham &lt;/em&gt;may be wrestling, but for this season, it’s really good wrestling.&lt;/p&gt;&amp;#13;
&amp;#13;
&amp;#13;
