<title>KFC Doesn’t Chicken Out of Social Media Stunt</title>
<link>https://www.geek.com/tech/kfc-doesnt-chicken-out-of-social-media-stunt-1722300/?source</link>
<guid isPermaLink="true" >https://www.geek.com/tech/kfc-doesnt-chicken-out-of-social-media-stunt-1722300/?source</guid>
<description>&lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;The Internet is a weird and wonderful place. Just ask Mike Edgette, the proud new owner of a gold-framed portrait of himself, holding a piece of chicken while riding on KFC founder Col. Harland Sanders’ back.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&amp;#13;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;The South Dakotan recently spotted a hidden Easter egg in the fast food chain’s Twitter account.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&amp;#13;
&amp;#13;
&lt;div class=&quot;flex-video widescreen embed&quot; readability=&quot;7.469696969697&quot;&gt;
&lt;blockquote class=&quot;twitter-tweet&quot; data-width=&quot;500&quot; readability=&quot;8.7878787878788&quot;&gt;&amp;#13;
&lt;p lang=&quot;en&quot; dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;.&lt;a href=&quot;https://twitter.com/kfc?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw&quot;&gt;@KFC&lt;/a&gt; follows 11 people.&lt;/p&gt;&amp;#13;
&lt;p&gt;Those 11 people? 5 Spice Girls and 6 guys named Herb.&lt;/p&gt;&amp;#13;
&lt;p&gt;11 Herbs &amp;amp; Spices. I need time to process this.&lt;/p&gt;&amp;#13;
&amp;#13;
&lt;p&gt;— Edge (@edgette22) &lt;a href=&quot;https://twitter.com/edgette22/status/921103567771131904?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw&quot;&gt;October 19, 2017&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&amp;#13;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;

&lt;/div&gt;&amp;#13;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;Edgette’s tweet went viral, blowing the minds of social media users, and garnering attention from KFC itself.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&amp;#13;
&amp;#13;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;Details of their private conversation were not released. But presumably it involved the promise of some kind of reward, and Edgette providing a Sioux Falls address where he could receive it.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&amp;#13;
&amp;#13;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;Two weeks later, a “giant” package appeared on his porch. Inside: a 2.5-foot-by-2-foot painting of Col. Sanders, Edgette, and a scenic mountain view.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&amp;#13;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;“There was no explanation as to why I’m piggybacking the Colonel,” Edgette &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.argusleader.com/story/news/2017/11/08/kfc-creates-painting-sioux-falls-man-who-tweeted-its-herbs-and-spices/843421001&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;noopener&quot;&gt;told local newspaper&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;em&gt;&lt;span&gt;Argus Leader&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;span&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&amp;#13;
&amp;#13;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;There was, however, 52 $5 gift cards, and a bizarre letter from the late Sanders (who died in 1980).&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&amp;#13;
&amp;#13;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;“This is a painting that I painted, with paint. And yet, it’s somehow more than that,” according to the note, as published by the&lt;/span&gt; &lt;em&gt;&lt;span&gt;Leader&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;span&gt;. “It’s a metaphor. It’s a tribute. It’s a long-awaited payoff for those years of art classes I took from Lisa in Accounting’s weird aunt.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&amp;#13;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;“But above all, it’s a thank you.”&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&amp;#13;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;The TallGrass Public Relations social media manager is still enjoying his 15 minutes of fame: Edgette has become the target of a &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.reddit.com/r/pics/comments/7bf2zk/kfc_comissioned_this_painting_for_the_man_who/dpho4q6&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;noopener&quot;&gt;Reddit conspiracy theory&lt;/a&gt;, suggesting this is all part of an elaborate marketing ploy. (To be fair, there&lt;/span&gt; &lt;em&gt;&lt;span&gt;are&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/em&gt; &lt;span&gt;still some unanswered questions, like where did KFC find a photo of Edgette for its design?)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&amp;#13;
&amp;#13;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;KFC is no stranger to odd promotions. In the last year alone, the company introduced a &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.geek.com/culture/celebrate-mothers-day-with-a-kfc-romance-novel-1698866/&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;noopener&quot;&gt;romance novel&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.geek.com/culture/kfc-counts-down-to-first-zinger-burger-in-space-1703398/&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;noopener&quot;&gt;launched a sandwich into space&lt;/a&gt;, debuted a &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.geek.com/culture/kfc-smartphone-looks-finger-lickin-good-1707211/&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;noopener&quot;&gt;branded smartphone&lt;/a&gt;, and dropped a &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.geek.com/culture/this-kfc-bath-bomb-will-have-you-smelling-like-fried-chicken-1721445/&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;noopener&quot;&gt;fried chicken-scented bath bomb&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&amp;#13;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;It delivered a real K.O. this fall, though, when the company started &lt;a href=&quot;https://twitter.com/kfc/following&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;noopener&quot;&gt;following only 11 people&lt;/a&gt; on Twitter: All five members of ’90s Brit-pop group Spice Girls (Geri Horner, Melanie Brown, Emma Bunton, Melanie Chisholm, Victoria Beckham) and six random dudes named Herb (including Green Bay Packers cornerback Herb Waters).&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&amp;#13;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;Get it? Eleven herbs and spices? Because KFC’s original chicken is seasoned with the Colonel’s secret recipe of 11 herbs and spices?&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&amp;#13;
&amp;#13;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;Pretty clever, if you ask me.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&amp;#13;
&amp;#13;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;Twitter user @laurelbartlettt technically beat Edgette to the punch, having &lt;a href=&quot;https://twitter.com/laurelbartlettt/status/919736811416518657&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;noopener&quot;&gt;stumbled upon the corporate gag&lt;/a&gt; four days earlier.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&amp;#13;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;“I was on their page (avid fan) and got curious [about] which 11 people were lucky enough to be followed by KFC,” she wrote on the microblogging site. But, her tweet didn’t gain as much traction as Edgette’s, and she missed the opportunity for a truly epic work of art.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&amp;#13;
&amp;#13;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;Let us know what you like about Geek by &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.research.net/r/geeksocnps&quot;&gt;taking our survey&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&amp;#13;
</description>
<pubDate>Fri, 10 Nov 2017 15:00:05 +0000</pubDate>
<dc:creator>Stephanie Mlot</dc:creator>
