&lt;h2&gt;9/20/2017&lt;/h2&gt;&amp;#13;
&amp;#13;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;img class=&quot;aligncenter size-medium wp-image-1716770&quot; src=&quot;https://www.geek.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/09/gaming-glasses-625x350.jpg&quot; alt=&quot; Gunnar Optiks PPK Unisex Gaming Glasses&quot; width=&quot;625&quot; height=&quot;350&quot; srcset=&quot;https://www.geek.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/09/gaming-glasses.jpg 625w, https://www.geek.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/09/gaming-glasses-300x168.jpg 300w, https://www.geek.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/09/gaming-glasses-141x80.jpg 141w, https://www.geek.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/09/gaming-glasses-130x73.jpg 130w&quot; sizes=&quot;(max-width: 625px) 100vw, 625px&quot;/&gt;&lt;br/&gt;&amp;#13;
I know what you’re thinking -why the heck do you need a special pair of glasses for gaming? Here’s the deal: the human eye is suited for taking in a wide range of visible light across the spectrum. But when we spend a lot of time looking at a screen, it’s mostly what they call “blue light,” which has been scientifically shown to increase the risk of macular degeneration, cataracts, and other nasty stuff. At this price, they’re worth a try.&lt;/p&gt;&amp;#13;
&lt;p&gt;$34.58 from Amazon Prime, &lt;a href=&quot;https://r.zdbb.net/u/3445&quot;&gt;Buy it here&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&amp;#13;
