<title>Rian Johnson Will Create a New Star Wars Trilogy, New TV Series Also Coming</title>
<link>https://www.geek.com/movies/rian-johnson-will-create-a-new-star-wars-trilogy-new-tv-series-also-coming-1722263/?source</link>
<guid isPermaLink="true" >https://www.geek.com/movies/rian-johnson-will-create-a-new-star-wars-trilogy-new-tv-series-also-coming-1722263/?source</guid>
<description>&lt;div class=&quot;figure&quot; readability=&quot;7&quot;&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAAAAAAP///yH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAIBRAA7&quot; data-src=&quot;[https://www.geek.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/11/rian-johnson-tall-C-650x366.jpg,(default)],[https://www.geek.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/11/rian-johnson-tall-C-625x352.jpg,(small)]&quot; width=&quot;650&quot; height=&quot;366&quot;/&gt;&lt;noscript&gt;&amp;#13;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;https://www.geek.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/11/rian-johnson-tall-C-650x366.jpg&quot; width=&quot;650&quot; height=&quot;366&quot;/&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&amp;#13;
&lt;/noscript&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Rian Johnson (Via StarWars.com)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;article readability=&quot;55.965903555772&quot;&gt;&amp;#13;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Star Wars: The Last Jedi &lt;/em&gt;isn’t out yet, but Rian Johnson already has his next project lined up. From the looks of things the director is going to stick around the Star Wars universe for a while. &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.starwars.com/news/rian-johnson-writer-director-of-star-wars-the-last-jedi-to-create-all-new-star-wars-trilogy?cmp=smc%7C1147744441&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;noopener&quot;&gt;Disney and LucasFilm announced&lt;/a&gt; today that Johnson will take the helm of directorial control for the foreseeable future. Since Disney bought Lucasfilm in 2012, everyone knew their plans extended far beyond a third trilogy of movies. Of course, they were going to finish up the Skywalker family story, but nobody could say what the company had planned after &lt;em&gt;Episode IX. &lt;/em&gt;The only thing we knew for certain: Disney would keep making more Star Wars movies long after we were all dead.&lt;/p&gt;&amp;#13;
&lt;p&gt;Johnson will write and direct the first film in the new trilogy, and his longtime collaborator Ram Bergman will produce. Not much is known right now about the new trilogy except for the fact that it will have nothing to do with the Skywalker story. That’s probably a good thing. By the time we reach the end of the current trilogy, we’ll have spent nine movies with this family. It sounds like it’ll also introduce new planets as well. The statement promises new characters “from a corner of the galaxy that Star Wars lore has never before explored.” Well, that sounds exciting.&lt;/p&gt;&amp;#13;
&amp;#13;
&lt;p&gt;LucasFilm president Kathleen Kennedy said in a statement, “We all loved working with Rian on &lt;em&gt;The Last Jedi. &lt;/em&gt;He’s a creative force, and watching him craft &lt;em&gt;The Last Jedi &lt;/em&gt;from start to finish was one of the great joys of my career. Rian will do amazing things with the blank canvas of this new trilogy.”&lt;/p&gt;&amp;#13;
&lt;p&gt;Though &lt;em&gt;The Last Jedi &lt;/em&gt;is just under two months away, this gives us some pretty high hopes for the eight episode in the Star Wars saga. Johnson must have made one spectacular film for LucasFilm to give him their next whole trilogy to shape. Not that this would be a surprise. Johnson is a fantastic sci-fi director. If you haven’t seen &lt;em&gt;Looper, &lt;/em&gt;I’d definitely recommend watching it right now. It’s seriously one of the coolest, most thoughtful and most fun time travel movies of the decade. With Johnson helming an entirely new Star Wars trilogy, I’m almost looking forward to that more than I am Episodes VIII and IX. Now the question is, how will they number the new trilogy. Since it’s an entirely different story will it be Episode I? Or will Johnson follow George Lucas’ lead and start with Episode IV?&lt;/p&gt;&amp;#13;
&lt;p&gt;There’s no release date yet, but given the frequency with which Star Wars movies have been coming out, I’d look for it sometime in 2021.&lt;/p&gt;&amp;#13;
&amp;#13;
&lt;div id=&quot;attachment_1722267&quot; class=&quot;wp-caption alignnone&quot; readability=&quot;32&quot;&gt;&lt;img class=&quot;size-full wp-image-1722267&quot; src=&quot;https://www.geek.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/11/porg_f5e77ddb.jpeg&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; width=&quot;690&quot; height=&quot;388&quot; srcset=&quot;https://www.geek.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/11/porg_f5e77ddb.jpeg 690w, https://www.geek.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/11/porg_f5e77ddb-300x169.jpeg 300w, https://www.geek.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/11/porg_f5e77ddb-625x352.jpeg 625w, https://www.geek.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/11/porg_f5e77ddb-650x366.jpeg 650w, https://www.geek.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/11/porg_f5e77ddb-141x80.jpeg 141w, https://www.geek.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/11/porg_f5e77ddb-130x73.jpeg 130w&quot; sizes=&quot;(max-width: 690px) 100vw, 690px&quot;/&gt;&lt;p class=&quot;wp-caption-text&quot;&gt;I hope the new corner of the galaxy has PORGS! (Via StarWars.com)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;&amp;#13;
&lt;p&gt;That’s not the only piece of Star Wars news to come out today. &lt;em&gt;Variety &lt;/em&gt;reports that in an earnings call, Disney CEO Bob Iger announced a new live-action Star Wars TV series. There’s no word on what the series is going to be, but it will be on Disney’s upcoming standalone streaming service. Yeah, I know, another streaming service. Everyone’s doing one, and to make matters worse, they all seem to be developing really good shows to get you to subscribe. Warner Bros. is doing &lt;em&gt;Titans &lt;/em&gt;for their DC-branded service. CBS All Access has &lt;em&gt;Star Trek: Discovery. &lt;/em&gt;Now Disney will have the Star Wars live-action TV series and there’s no way we’re going to miss out on that. LucasFilm has been trying to make that happen for years, and the massive budget it would require has kept any network from biting. It being on a Disney-owned subscription service might be the thing that makes it possible.&lt;/p&gt;&amp;#13;
&lt;p&gt;There’s no word on whether the Star Wars series will be ready for Disney’s planned launch of their streaming platform in late 2019. It’d be cool if it turned out to be that &lt;em&gt;Star Wars: Underworld &lt;/em&gt;show George Lucas was working on in the years before Disney bought everything. They have the scripts ready to go and that show sounded pretty great. No matter what, we have a ton of Star Wars coming our way in the next few years. I can’t complain about that.&lt;/p&gt;&amp;#13;
&lt;/article&gt;&lt;footer class=&quot;tags-share&quot;&gt;&amp;#13;
&amp;#13;
&lt;/footer&gt;</description>
<pubDate>Thu, 09 Nov 2017 23:08:34 +0000</pubDate>
<dc:creator>Nick Mangione</dc:creator>
